# TypeScript Standards

## Type Safety
- Never use `any` — use `unknown`, generics, or proper types
- Prefer `interface` for object shapes (extendable), `type` for unions and complex types
- Always type function parameters and return values for exported functions

## Patterns
```typescript
// Bad
const processData = (data: any) => data.value;

// Good
const processData = <T extends { value: string }>(data: T): string => data.value;

// Bad: unused imports/variables
import { unused } from './module';

// Good: prefix unused params with _
const handler = (_event: Event, data: Data) => process(data);
```

## Avoid
- `as` type assertions (prefer type guards or generics)
- Non-null assertions (`!`) unless absolutely certain
- `// @ts-ignore` — fix the type error instead
- Enums — prefer union types or `as const` objects
